00:47:38.230 --> 00:47:41.490
And there's a line of work I didn't get to
talk about in this talk that we call Digital

00:47:41.490 --> 00:47:46.630
Footprints and this how many guys have seen
this New Yorker comic on the Internet "nobody

00:47:46.630 --> 00:47:51.069
knows you're a dog" that shows a dog on the
Internet.

00:47:51.069 --> 00:47:56.329
We've run a study actually the military is
actually sponsoring a huge program with lots

00:47:56.329 --> 00:48:00.069
and lots of people studying this which is
based on what I call your digital footprint

00:48:00.069 --> 00:48:02.670
which is the stuff you leave behind in a virtual
world.

00:48:02.670 --> 00:48:04.710
So on a web you leave behind cookies.

00:48:04.710 --> 00:48:09.170
In a virtual world you leave behind where
you walked, everything you've said.

00:48:09.170 --> 00:48:13.550
So in this online world Second Life you can
record everything everybody does; who they're

00:48:13.550 --> 00:48:16.460
standing next to, if they're flying or walking.

00:48:16.460 --> 00:48:20.940
We've run studies now -- I ran a study where
I took 80 Stanford students.

00:48:20.940 --> 00:48:22.930
They spent 10 hours a week in Second Life.

00:48:22.930 --> 00:48:27.630
And they put on these buttons that recorded
everything they ever did in Second Life.

00:48:27.630 --> 00:48:29.829
But I also knew who they were in the first
world.

00:48:29.829 --> 00:48:30.829
They were my students.

00:48:30.829 --> 00:48:34.110
I knew their gender, I knew their age, I knew
their GPA, I knew their major.

00:48:34.110 --> 00:48:36.380
I knew they fill that personality metrics.

00:48:36.380 --> 00:48:40.770
And then what we then did is we used machine
learning algorithms which are statistical

00:48:40.770 --> 00:48:45.990
methods where you can correlate data with
a right and wrong answer.

00:48:45.990 --> 00:48:49.650
And what we did is we said can I use this
digital footprint, this massive amount of

00:48:49.650 --> 00:48:51.500
data we're collecting on a second/second basis.

00:48:51.500 --> 00:48:56.220
Think about this: 80 student students,ten
hours a week, every second collecting about

00:48:56.220 --> 00:48:58.599
50 parameters on what they're doing in the
virtual world.

00:48:58.599 --> 00:49:04.670
Can you take all that data and find me some
pattern that I can detect a man from a woman.

00:49:04.670 --> 00:49:08.780
Can how you walk in Second Life, does that
tell me your gender or your age.

00:49:08.780 --> 00:49:15.320
And what we demonstrated with extremely high
accuracies much higher than I thought possible,

00:49:15.320 --> 00:49:20.849
I can tell a lot about you, your personality,
your race, based on things we thought were

00:49:20.849 --> 00:49:21.849
anonymous.

00:49:21.849 --> 00:49:25.720
So the joke is yes you may think that on the
Internet nobody knows you're a dog but it

00:49:25.720 --> 00:49:28.059
turns out we know you're a dog.

00:49:28.059 --> 00:49:29.609
We know quite well.

00:49:29.609 --> 00:49:35.380
The Internet and virtual worlds in particular
have this illusion of being anonymous.

00:49:35.380 --> 00:49:37.530
Everything -- it's not me it's an avatar.

00:49:37.530 --> 00:49:41.430
But it turns out the digital footprint you
leave behind in a virtual world, is more damning,

00:49:41.430 --> 00:49:46.430
in many ways, or depending on the point of
view more wonderful, than any face to face

00:49:46.430 --> 00:49:50.900
encounter could be because there's a record
of every single behavior done by every person.

00:49:50.900 --> 00:49:55.450
Whereas face to face, I can do something embarrassing
but I can lobby later on for all of you not

00:49:55.450 --> 00:49:59.200
to tell anybody; but in a virtual world that
doesn't work.

